description: Fruit and vegetable farms grow and distribute fruit or vegetables
Livestock farms raise animals and sell them at auction or take them to abattoirs
Arable farms grow and harvest crops
Beekeepers keep bees in hives and extract honey from them
Honey makers extract and package honey for national retail
Hunters and trappers hunt and trap wild animals for food
Egg processors manufacture or process egg products and distributes them nationally
Egg producers or packers have birds for egg laying and distributes eggs locally
Fishing boats fish and catch seafood for food
Fish farms raise fish and other species in water for food
Meat product manufacturers produce preserved meats or meat based products. For example sausages or freezed meat.
Abattoirs are where livestock animals go to slaughter. Contact your local council for approval

dataName: Processing and preserving of fish, crustaceans and molluscs
description: Fish and shellfish product manufacturers process seafood, for example freeze it or make fishfingers
Shellfish purification centres treat seafood to remove impurites and contaminates
Potato product manufacturers process poatatoes, for example cuts and freeze it or make crisps

dataName: Manufacture of fruit and vegetable juice
description: Fruit and vegetable juice manufacturers make drinks from fruit and vegetable. For example juice or smoothies.

dataName: Other processing and preserving of fruit and vegetables
description: Fruit and vegetable product manufacturers process fruit or vegetables. For example tinned fruit, bags of salad leafs or vegan products.
Oil and/or fat manufacturers process vegetable oil or animal fat to produce products. For example olive oil or lard

dataName: Operation of dairies and cheese making
description: Dairy or cheese manufacturers makes products such as yoghurt or cheddar
Ice cream manufacturers make products such as ice cream or gelato
Commercial bakeries make products such as bread, cookies, cakes and pastries and distributes them nationally. They have no on-site shop.

dataName: Manufacture of prepared meals and dishes
displayName: Ready to eat meals or food manufacturer
description: Ready to eat meals manufacturers process different products to make food that is generally ready to eat for the consumer. Processes include for example canning, cooking, chilling or freezing.

dataName: Manufacture of homogenised food preparations and dietetic food
description: Dietetic or baby food manufacturers makes food that is either specific to a certain diet, for example gluten free foods, or food that is blended smooth, for example baby food or protein drinks

dataName: Manufacture of other food products n.e.c.
description: Manufacturer of other food products make products such as coffee, infant formula, mayonnaise or uncooked pizza. If you couldn't find any other fitting manufacturer type on the previous page, this is the best selection for you.
Alcoholic drinks manufacturers makes drinks containing alcohol. For example beer, gin or wine.

dataName: Manufacture-Soft drinks, mineral waters and other bottled waters
description: Non alcoholic drinks manufacturers makes drinks containing no alcohol. For example lemonade, milkshakes or energy drinks.
Mineral water packers bottle still or sparkling water, and supply other businesses
Contract packers package food on behalf of someone else and are not involved in processing food. Methods of packing include for example canning, bottling or wrapping.

dataName: Food delivery service-Deliver food to consumers
description: Food delivery services transports the food from a business to the end consumer. They do not make food themselves.

dataName: Food delivery service-Process food order only for consumers, e.g. Just Eat
description: Food ordering services process food orders on behalf of someone else to deliver it. They do not have any physical contact with the food.
Food storage facilities store food. Some may use temperature controlled environments, such as cold stores.
Food brokers arrange transactions between seller and buyer. They take legal ownership of the food, but never physical.
Wholesalers primarily sells food products to other food businesses, and delivers locally or regionally
Cash and carry primarily sells food products to other food businesses. Both local and non-local businesses visit and transport the food themselves.
Haulage companies move food products between locations on behalf of customers
Online retailers sell food products via the internet. The products are distributed nationally and are generally not temperature controlled.
Supermarkets sell prepackaged food as well as open food, for example bake off bread or delicatessen, to local customers

displayName: Local convenience store or corner shop
description: Local convenience stores or corner shops sell prepackaged food to local customers
Farm gate sales sells shelf stable products such as eggs or potatoes on a small scale from the farm
Fark shops prepare, cook or handle food and serve it to customers
Sweet shops or confectioners retail prepackaged food
Butchers prepare, cook or handle open foods, such as meat, pies or sausages, alongside general butchering.
Fishmongers prepare, cook or handle open seafoods, such as smoked fish, alongside selling raw seafood
Greengrocers sell fruit and vegetables as well as other shelf stable products
Health food shops sell low risk foods and other shelf stable food products. For example dried herbs or fruit
Bakeries prepare, cook or handle open food items. For example bread, cookies or cakes
Newsagents or Post Offices retail prepackaged food
Market stalls with a permanent location sell food products from a regular pitch
Off licences sell low risk foods and other shelf stable items. For example sweets, drinks or crisps.
Petrol stations or garages sell prepackaged food as well as open food. For example bake off bread.
Delicatessens prepare cook or handle open high risk food, such as hams, cheeses for sandwiches
Chemists retails prepackaged and shelf stable foods, as a part of their regular business
Any other retailers retail pre packaged or shelf stable food items. If you couldn't find any other fitting retailer type on the previous page, this is the best selection for you.
Vending machines dispense prepackaged food products. For example sweets, crisps or drinks.

displayName: Restaurant, cafe, canteen or fast food
description: Restaurants, cafes, canteens, or fast food restaurants prepare, cook or handle food. For example pizza, soup or pies.
Hostels or Bed and Breakfasts serve cooked or continental breakfasts
Hotels prepare, cook or handle food and serve it to customers
Pubs serving meals serve alcoholic drinks to local customers and prepare, cook or handle food to be eaten on site

displayName: Pub serving only snacks and drinks
description: Pubs serving only snacks and drinks

dataName: Take away-No food consumed on site
displayName: Take away with no food consumed on site
description: Takeaways with no food consumed on site prepare, cook or handle food and serve customers that come and pick up food to eat off-site

displayName: Nursing home, care home or day centre
description: Nursing homes, care homes or day centres prepare, cook or handle food and serve meals to their customers. These customers are considered vulnerable, for example elderly, children or the ill.
Hospitals cook or handle food and serve meals to patients. These patients are vulnerable, for example the ill.
Childminders cook or handle food and serve meals to children under five years

dataName: Childcare, Nursery; pre/after school care; play group etc-Meals
description: Childcare, nurseries or playgroups prepare, cook or handle and serve food to children under five years
Educational establishments prepare, cook or handle food and serve their students
Mobile retailers handle, but do not cook, pre packed food. For example jams, sandwiches or drinks.
Mobile caterers prepare, cook or handle food. For example pizza, scooped ice cream or curry.
Movable food establishments prepare, cook or handle food on a movable premises, such as trains, boats or airplanes. They serve a substantial number of national or international customer every day.
Contract caterers prepare, cook or handle food at events or at a dedicated location, such as a staff canteen
Home caterers cook or prepare food from home

displayName: Meat cutting plant or commercial butcher
description: Meat cutting plants or commercial butchers butcher carcasses for sale to other businesses
Food auction halls is an auction hall for the sale of food, such as fish or meat, generally to business customers
